dalserver.sla

Class SlapServlet

  • java.lang.Object
    • HttpServlet
      • dalserver.sla.SlapServlet

  • public class SlapServlet
extends HttpServlet
    Generic HTTP Servlet for the SLAP protocol. By default this service merely implements a data query and returns a query response, but never finds any data. If properly configured, this generic SLAP class also has the ability to query a DBMS for list list metadata, implementing a real SLAP service for line lists which conform to the standard data model.

    This is a generic HTTP servlet which implements an SLAP service using the service implementation provided by the generic SlapService class. By default it merely echoes its input arguments and defines and return an empty VOTable containing all predefined SLAP table fields. To turn this into a real data service, one can either configure it (in the servlet web.xml) to query a local DBMS to find precomputed list list data, or subclass the service to implement a custom SLAP service with arbitrary functionality.

    To implement a custom service (in src/dataServices) one would 1) subclass SlapService and modify it as necessary to query a real data collection, and 2) subclass this class (SlapServlet) and override the newSlapService method to call the custom SlapService class provided in step 1). The modified Servlet class should then be runnable in any compliant Java application server such as Apache Tomcat.

    • Field Detail

      • serviceName

        protected java.lang.String serviceName
        The name of the service or servlet instance. This is used to construct file names for service-specific configuration files. For example, if we have two different SLAP service instances these should have distinct service names. Defined locally in the servlet deployment descriptor (web.xml). Optional.

      • serviceVersion

        protected java.lang.String serviceVersion
        The default service interface version supported by the service if no version number is explicitly negotiated. This is usually the highest standard interface version supported by the service. Defined locally in the servlet deployment descriptor (web.xml).

      • configDir

        protected java.lang.String configDir
        The directory on the local server machine used to store runtime service configuration files, e.g., for the getCapabilities method. Defined locally in the servlet deployment descriptor (web.xml).

      • dataDirURL

        protected java.lang.String dataDirURL
        A directory (referenced by URL) on the local server machine used to store precomputed archival datasets to be returned by the built-in getData method. Most services will require a more sophisticated means to return data, but this technique is provided to provide a simple built-in getData capability for testing. Defined locally in the servlet deployment descriptor (web.xml). Optional.

      • contentType

        protected java.lang.String contentType
        The content (MIME) type to be used for any datasets retrieved from the dataDir. If set to DYNAMIC, the service will attempt to dynamically determine the content type of each file.

      • dbType

        protected java.lang.String dbType
        The type of database to be accessed, e.g., "MySQL", "PostgreSQL", or "builtin". For the most part JDBC hides the difference between DBMS implementations, but not entirely.

      • dbName

        protected java.lang.String dbName
        The name of the database to be accessed. By "database" we mean a SQL catalog or schema containing tables.

      • tableName

        protected java.lang.String tableName
        The name of the table to be accessed by the service.

      • jdbcUrl

        protected java.lang.String jdbcUrl
        The JDBC URL of the database server, e.g., "jdbc:mysql://:3306/".

      • jdbcDriver

        protected java.lang.String jdbcDriver
        The address of the JDBC driver to be used, e.g., "com.mysql.jdbc.Driver".

      • dbUser

        protected java.lang.String dbUser
        The user name to be used to login to the DBMS.

      • dbPassword

        protected java.lang.String dbPassword
        The password to be used to login to the DBMS. This should not be a real user password, but rather the password of a DBMS account used to provide low security, read-only access the database.

      • newSlapService

        public SlapService newSlapService(SlapParamSet params)
        Get a new SlapService instance. By default the generic dataless SlapService class is used. To build a real data service, subclass SlapServlet and replace the newSlapService method with one which calls a custom replacement for the builtin generic SlapService class.

        This version includes the dataDir and dataType parameters, used to implement a simple mechanism (see SlapService.getData(dalserver.sla.SlapParamSet, dalserver.RequestResponse) for returning static precomputed archival files from local storage on the server.

        Parameters:
        params - The input and service parameters.

      • newSlapParamSet

        public SlapParamSet newSlapParamSet()
                             throws DalServerException
        Get a new empty SlapParamSet instance. This can be specialized by the sub-class to add service-specific inputs.

        This version returns a generic SlapParamSet.

        Throws:
        DalServerException
